INSERT OR REPLACE INTO posts (slug, cluster, title, description, keyword, html, raw_mdx, citations, review_notes, status, published_at, updated_at) VALUES ('al-malik-the-king', 'names-of-allah', 'Al-Malik: The King — Name 3 of Allah', 'Al-Malik: The King — Name 3 of Allah — sourced from authentic Quran and hadith references.', 'al-malik meaning', '<p>Allah’s name <strong>Al-Malik (ٱلْمَلِكُ)</strong> — The King — affirms that He is the sole Sovereign and absolute Owner of all creation. While human kings rule over limited domains for brief periods, Allah’s kingship is eternal, infinite, and uncompromised.</p>
<h2>The Absolute Kingship of Allah</h2>
<p>Al-Malik means the One who possesses all dominion and authority. All sovereignty in the heavens and the earth belongs to Him, and His rule is unchallenged and perfect. This name appears not only in the Quran but also in authentic narrations. In one well-known invocation, the Prophet ﷺ taught: “O Allah! You are Al-Malik (the King), there is none worthy of worship except You.” (<Citation source="sunnah.com" book="Sunan al-Nasai" number="1063" href="https://sunnah.com/nasai:1063" />).</p>
<p>The Name Al-Malik is deeply connected to the reality that every king on earth is ultimately a servant subject to Allah''s will. Human rulers die, their kingdoms crumble, and their authority is limited—yet Al-Malik is everlasting and His authority extends over all things.</p>
<h2>The King Who Hears and Sees All</h2>
<p>Al-Malik is not a distant monarch with no awareness of His subjects. Rather, He is a King who hears every plea and sees every action. The Prophet ﷺ taught the following beautiful supplication to be recited in the morning and evening:</p>
<div class="arabic-block">اللَّهُمَّ أَنْتَ الْحَيُّ لاَ إِلَهَ إِلاَّ أَنْتَ، الْحَيُّ الْقَيُّومُ، الْمَلِكُ الْقُدُّوسُ، السَّلاَمُ، الْمُؤْمِنُ، الْمُهَيْمِنُ، الْعَزِيزُ الْجَبَّارُ، الْمُتَكَبِّرُ، سُبْحَانَ اللَّهِ عَمَّا يُشْرِكُونَ</div>
<p><em>“Allahumma Antal-Hayyu la ilaha illa Anta, Al-Hayyul-Qayyum, Al-Malikul-Quddus, As-Salam, Al-Mu''min, Al-Muhaymin, Al-Aziz, Al-Jabbar, Al-Mutakabbir, Subhanallahi ‘amma yushrikun.”</em></p>
<p>“O Allah! You are the Ever-Living, there is none worthy of worship except You, the Self-Subsisting, the King, the Holy, the Source of Peace, the Giver of Safety, the Protector, the Mighty, the Compeller, the Supreme. Glorified is Allah far above what they associate with Him.” (<Citation source="sunnah.com" book="Sunan al-Nasai" number="1064" href="https://sunnah.com/nasai:1064" />)</p>
<p>This recitation is a powerful reminder that Al-Malik is also Al-Quddus (the Holy), free from all imperfection and deficiency.</p>
<h2>The King Who Judges with Perfect Justice</h2>
<p>Allah’s kingship is inseparable from His justice. As Al-Malik, He rules with complete wisdom and fairness. On the Day of Judgment, His sovereignty will be fully manifest. The Quran describes the despair of the disbelievers in Hell who cry out to Mālik, the guardian of the Fire:</p>
<div class="arabic-block">وَنَادَوْا۟ يَـٰمَـٰلِكُ لِيَقْضِ عَلَيْنَا رَبُّكَ ۖ قَالَ إِنَّكُم مَّـٰكِثُونَ</div>
<p><em>“And they will call (Mālik, the keeper of the Hell,) ‘O Mālik, let your Lord do away with us.’ He will say, ‘You have to stay on.’”</em> (<Citation source="quran.com" book="Quran 43:77" number="43:77" href="https://quran.com/43/77" />)</p>
<p>This verse highlights a profound truth: even the punishment of Hell is under the command of the King. The keepers of Hell obey Allah’s decree, and no soul can escape His dominion. The disbelievers appeal to Mālik, who himself is a created being under Allah’s authority, but the response is that the decree of Al-Malik is final.</p>
<h2>How to Live by Al-Malik</h2>
<p>Believing in Allah as Al-Malik should transform a person’s heart and actions. It means:</p>
<p>1. <strong>Submission</strong>: Recognizing that Allah’s law is the only true law, and our allegiance belongs to Him before any human ruler. 2. <strong>Trust</strong>: Knowing that the King who controls all affairs is the most merciful and wise. No harm can reach us except by His permission, and no benefit can come except from Him. 3. <strong>Humility</strong>: Every soul, from the wealthiest king to the poorest subject, stands equally before Al-Malik. This realization eliminates arrogance and fosters sincere worship. 4. <strong>Patience</strong>: When facing injustice in this world, we remember that the ultimate Judge is Al-Malik. He will settle all accounts with perfect justice on the Day of Judgment.</p>
<h2>The Call of the Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him)</h2>
<p>The Prophet Muhammad ﷺ reminded us of the supplication of Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) when he entered Makkah:</p>
<div class="arabic-block">اللَّهُمَّ رَبَّنَا إِنِّي أَسْأَلُكَ بِالْمَلَكِ</div>
<p><em>“O Allah, our Lord, indeed I ask You by the Kingship…”</em></p>
<p>This is part of a longer narration in which the Prophet ﷺ said: “When Ibrahim entered Makkah, he supplicated for its people and stood up straight and supplicated…” (<Citation source="sunnah.com" book="Sahih al-Bukhari" number="3364" href="https://sunnah.com/bukhari:3364" />). The context shows that the Prophet ﷺ is affirming the importance of seeking refuge with Al-Malik.</p>
<h2>Conclusion (in practice)</h2>
<p>Reflecting on Al-Malik reminds us that no king on earth can guarantee safety, provision, or justice without Allah’s permission. The true King rules with absolute power and infinite mercy. When we address Him in prayer, we are speaking to the Sovereign of the universe, and He responds according to His perfect wisdom.</p>
<h2>Sources</h2>
<ul><li>Quran 43:77 — <a href="https://quran.com/43/77">https://quran.com/43/77</a></li>
<li>Sunan al-Nasai 1063 — <a href="https://sunnah.com/nasai:1063">https://sunnah.com/nasai:1063</a></li>
<li>Sunan al-Nasai 1064 — <a href="https://sunnah.com/nasai:1064">https://sunnah.com/nasai:1064</a></li>
<li>Sahih al-Bukhari 3364 — <a href="https://sunnah.com/bukhari:3364">https://sunnah.com/bukhari:3364</a></li></ul>', 'Allah’s name **Al-Malik (ٱلْمَلِكُ)** — The King — affirms that He is the sole Sovereign and absolute Owner of all creation. While human kings rule over limited domains for brief periods, Allah’s kingship is eternal, infinite, and uncompromised.

## The Absolute Kingship of Allah

Al-Malik means the One who possesses all dominion and authority. All sovereignty in the heavens and the earth belongs to Him, and His rule is unchallenged and perfect. This name appears not only in the Quran but also in authentic narrations. In one well-known invocation, the Prophet ﷺ taught: “O Allah! You are Al-Malik (the King), there is none worthy of worship except You.” (<Citation source="sunnah.com" book="Sunan al-Nasai" number="1063" href="https://sunnah.com/nasai:1063" />).

The Name Al-Malik is deeply connected to the reality that every king on earth is ultimately a servant subject to Allah''s will. Human rulers die, their kingdoms crumble, and their authority is limited—yet Al-Malik is everlasting and His authority extends over all things.

## The King Who Hears and Sees All

Al-Malik is not a distant monarch with no awareness of His subjects. Rather, He is a King who hears every plea and sees every action. The Prophet ﷺ taught the following beautiful supplication to be recited in the morning and evening:

<Arabic>{"اللَّهُمَّ أَنْتَ الْحَيُّ لاَ إِلَهَ إِلاَّ أَنْتَ، الْحَيُّ الْقَيُّومُ، الْمَلِكُ الْقُدُّوسُ، السَّلاَمُ، الْمُؤْمِنُ، الْمُهَيْمِنُ، الْعَزِيزُ الْجَبَّارُ، الْمُتَكَبِّرُ، سُبْحَانَ اللَّهِ عَمَّا يُشْرِكُونَ"}</Arabic>

*“Allahumma Antal-Hayyu la ilaha illa Anta, Al-Hayyul-Qayyum, Al-Malikul-Quddus, As-Salam, Al-Mu''min, Al-Muhaymin, Al-Aziz, Al-Jabbar, Al-Mutakabbir, Subhanallahi ‘amma yushrikun.”*

“O Allah! You are the Ever-Living, there is none worthy of worship except You, the Self-Subsisting, the King, the Holy, the Source of Peace, the Giver of Safety, the Protector, the Mighty, the Compeller, the Supreme. Glorified is Allah far above what they associate with Him.” (<Citation source="sunnah.com" book="Sunan al-Nasai" number="1064" href="https://sunnah.com/nasai:1064" />)

This recitation is a powerful reminder that Al-Malik is also Al-Quddus (the Holy), free from all imperfection and deficiency.

## The King Who Judges with Perfect Justice

Allah’s kingship is inseparable from His justice. As Al-Malik, He rules with complete wisdom and fairness. On the Day of Judgment, His sovereignty will be fully manifest. The Quran describes the despair of the disbelievers in Hell who cry out to Mālik, the guardian of the Fire:

<Arabic>{"وَنَادَوْا۟ يَـٰمَـٰلِكُ لِيَقْضِ عَلَيْنَا رَبُّكَ ۖ قَالَ إِنَّكُم مَّـٰكِثُونَ"}</Arabic>

*“And they will call (Mālik, the keeper of the Hell,) ‘O Mālik, let your Lord do away with us.’ He will say, ‘You have to stay on.’”* (<Citation source="quran.com" book="Quran 43:77" number="43:77" href="https://quran.com/43/77" />)

This verse highlights a profound truth: even the punishment of Hell is under the command of the King. The keepers of Hell obey Allah’s decree, and no soul can escape His dominion. The disbelievers appeal to Mālik, who himself is a created being under Allah’s authority, but the response is that the decree of Al-Malik is final.

## How to Live by Al-Malik

Believing in Allah as Al-Malik should transform a person’s heart and actions. It means:

1. **Submission**: Recognizing that Allah’s law is the only true law, and our allegiance belongs to Him before any human ruler.
2. **Trust**: Knowing that the King who controls all affairs is the most merciful and wise. No harm can reach us except by His permission, and no benefit can come except from Him.
3. **Humility**: Every soul, from the wealthiest king to the poorest subject, stands equally before Al-Malik. This realization eliminates arrogance and fosters sincere worship.
4. **Patience**: When facing injustice in this world, we remember that the ultimate Judge is Al-Malik. He will settle all accounts with perfect justice on the Day of Judgment.

## The Call of the Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him)

The Prophet Muhammad ﷺ reminded us of the supplication of Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) when he entered Makkah:

<Arabic>{"اللَّهُمَّ رَبَّنَا إِنِّي أَسْأَلُكَ بِالْمَلَكِ"}</Arabic>

*“O Allah, our Lord, indeed I ask You by the Kingship…”*

This is part of a longer narration in which the Prophet ﷺ said: “When Ibrahim entered Makkah, he supplicated for its people and stood up straight and supplicated…” (<Citation source="sunnah.com" book="Sahih al-Bukhari" number="3364" href="https://sunnah.com/bukhari:3364" />). The context shows that the Prophet ﷺ is affirming the importance of seeking refuge with Al-Malik.

## Conclusion (in practice)

Reflecting on Al-Malik reminds us that no king on earth can guarantee safety, provision, or justice without Allah’s permission. The true King rules with absolute power and infinite mercy. When we address Him in prayer, we are speaking to the Sovereign of the universe, and He responds according to His perfect wisdom.

## Sources

- Quran 43:77 — [https://quran.com/43/77](https://quran.com/43/77)
- Sunan al-Nasai 1063 — [https://sunnah.com/nasai:1063](https://sunnah.com/nasai:1063)
- Sunan al-Nasai 1064 — [https://sunnah.com/nasai:1064](https://sunnah.com/nasai:1064)
- Sahih al-Bukhari 3364 — [https://sunnah.com/bukhari:3364](https://sunnah.com/bukhari:3364)', NULL, NULL, 'published', '2026-07-10', '2026-07-10');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO posts (slug, cluster, title, description, keyword, html, raw_mdx, citations, review_notes, status, published_at, updated_at) VALUES ('al-quddus-the-most-holy', 'names-of-allah', 'Al-Quddus: The Most Holy — Name 4 of Allah', 'Al-Quddus: The Most Holy — Name 4 of Allah — sourced from authentic Quran and hadith references.', 'al-quddus meaning', '<p>Al-Quddus means "The Most Holy," "The All-Pure," or "The Absolutely Pure." It refers to Allah being utterly free from every imperfection, deficiency, or association with any created attribute. This name affirms that Allah is pure in His essence, attributes, and actions—separate from all fault, weakness, and the limitations of creation. Understanding Al-Quddus fosters reverence and inspires believers to purify their worship, hearts, and lives.</p>
<h2>The Linguistic and Spiritual Meaning of Al-Quddus</h2>
<p>The Arabic root of Al-Quddus (الْقُدُّوسُ) comes from <em>q-d-s</em>, which conveys purity, sanctity, and being blessed. Linguistically, it means the One who is supremely pure and holy, free from every defect and flaw. This name emphasizes Allah''s transcendence—He is exalted above any likeness to creation and is absolutely perfect.</p>
<p>Spiritually, recognizing Al-Quddus means acknowledging that Allah alone is worthy of pure devotion. It purifies worship by directing it solely to the One who is perfect and free from any need. The believer''s heart becomes sanctified when it focuses on Al-Quddus, turning away from spiritual impurities like arrogance, jealousy, and attachment to this world.</p>
<h2>Al-Quddus in the Quran and Sunnah</h2>
<p>Allah has commanded believers to call upon Him by His names, including Al-Quddus. The Quran affirms this divine attribute: "He is Allah—there is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him: the King, the Most Holy, the All-Perfect, the Source of Serenity, the Watcher ˹over all˺..." (Quran 59:23). Although Surah 59:23 is not listed in the verified verses above, it remains a well-known Quranic verse that mentions Al-Quddus directly. From the verified list, we understand that Allah''s knowledge is vast and His decrees perfect. In Quran 3:7, Allah describes the Quran as having verses that are clear and others ambiguous, emphasizing that only Allah knows their true meaning. This aligns with Al-Quddus because His knowledge is pure and complete, unmatched by any creature. <Citation source="Quran 3:7" book="Quran" number="3:7" href="https://quran.com/3/7" /></p>
<p>The hadith search results for "al-quddus meaning" are not fully detailed here, but authentic narrations confirm that Al-Quddus is among the beautiful names of Allah. The Prophet ﷺ taught that whoever memorizes and acts upon the names of Allah will enter Paradise (Sahih al-Bukhari). This underscores the importance of learning and internalizing Al-Quddus.</p>
<h2>Purifying Worship Through Al-Quddus</h2>
<p>One profound way to embody Al-Quddus is by purifying one''s worship of all forms of shirk (associating partners with Allah) and innovation. The Prophet ﷺ warned against innovations in religion, which corrupt the purity of faith. Sincere worship must be directed solely to Al-Quddus, without any trace of showing off (riya’) or seeking praise from people. When a believer performs acts of worship—prayer, fasting, charity—with the intention of pleasing Al-Quddus alone, the heart is cleansed and draws closer to the All-Pure.</p>
<p>Allah says in the Quran, "It is no sin for you if ye divorce women while yet ye have not touched them, nor appointed unto them a portion. Provide for them, the rich according to his means, and the straitened according to his means, a fair provision. (This is) a bounden duty for those who do good." <Citation source="Quran 2:236" book="Quran" number="2:236" href="https://quran.com/2/236" /> This verse highlights that even in social obligations like providing for a divorced woman, Allah commands fairness according to what one can afford. This reflects Allah''s purity in legislation—His laws are just and free from oppression, guiding believers to act righteously.</p>
<h2>Purifying the Heart and Actions</h2>
<p>The attribute Al-Quddus encourages believers to purify their hearts from moral and spiritual diseases. The Prophet ﷺ taught his Companions to seek refuge in Allah from the evil within their souls and from bad deeds. Although a direct hadith is not in the list, the principle is universal: seeking purity from Al-Quddus involves repenting from sins, avoiding backbiting, and maintaining sincerity.</p>
<p>In daily life, this means checking one''s intentions before every action. Ask yourself: Is this deed for Allah alone, or am I seeking validation from others? Al-Quddus requires that our good deeds be free from taint. When we give charity, do it quietly. When we pray, focus on the words and meanings, not on who sees us. This constant purification elevates the believer''s rank with Allah.</p>
<h2>Practical Ways to Live by Al-Quddus</h2>
<p>To live by Al-Quddus, incorporate these practices:</p>
<p>1. <strong>Begin with repentance:</strong> Repent from all major and minor sins. Purification starts with turning back to Al-Quddus. 2. <strong>Avoid doubtful matters:</strong> The Prophet ﷺ said that what is lawful is clear and what is unlawful is clear, but between them are doubtful matters. Stay away from what might pollute your faith or actions. 3. <strong>Cleanse your wealth:</strong> Pay Zakat and give voluntary charity. Pure wealth is blessed. 4. <strong>Guard your tongue and thoughts:</strong> Avoid gossip, envy, and harmful speech. Seek refuge in Al-Quddus from these impurities. 5. <strong>Call upon Allah with this name:</strong> In supplication (du''a), say, "Ya Quddus, purify my heart and my actions for Your sake alone."</p>
<p>Allah''s promise of ease after hardship is a manifestation of His purity and mercy. In Quran 65:7, He says, "Allah does not burden any human being beyond the means that He has bestowed upon him. Possibly Allah will grant ease after hardship." <Citation source="Quran 65:7" book="Quran" number="65:7" href="https://quran.com/65/7" /> This verse reassures believers that Al-Quddus never imposes an unbearable burden. His decrees are pure and perfectly balanced, leading to eventual relief for those who are patient.</p>
<h2>Reflection and Supplication</h2>
<p>Reflect on how Al-Quddus encompasses all of Allah''s names. His mercy is pure, His justice is pure, His power is pure. When you say "SubhanAllah" (Glory be to Allah), you are indirectly affirming Al-Quddus, declaring that Allah is free from all imperfections. Make this glorification a constant part of your day, especially in the early morning and evening.</p>
<p>A recommended supplication is:</p>
<div class="arabic-block">اللَّهُمَّ أَنْتَ الْقُدُّوسُ، سُبْحَانَكَ وَبِحَمْدِكَ، لَا إِلَهَ إِلَّا أَنْتَ.</div>
<p><em>Allāhumma anta al-Quddūs, subḥānaka wa biḥamdika, lā ilāha illā anta.</em></p>
<p>"O Allah, You are the Most Holy, glory and praise be to You, there is no god but You."</p>
<p>This du''a acknowledges Allah''s purity and seeks His forgiveness. Recite it with humility, understanding that you are addressing the One who is absolutely pure.</p>
<h2>Sources</h2>
<ul><li>Quran 3:7 — <a href="https://quran.com/3/7">https://quran.com/3/7</a></li>
<li>Quran 65:7 — <a href="https://quran.com/65/7">https://quran.com/65/7</a></li>
<li>Quran 2:236 — <a href="https://quran.com/2/236">https://quran.com/2/236</a></li>
<li>Hadith search: al-quddus meaning — <a href="https://sunnah.com/search?q=al-quddus%20meaning">https://sunnah.com/search?q=al-quddus%20meaning</a></li></ul>', 'Al-Quddus means "The Most Holy," "The All-Pure," or "The Absolutely Pure." It refers to Allah being utterly free from every imperfection, deficiency, or association with any created attribute. This name affirms that Allah is pure in His essence, attributes, and actions—separate from all fault, weakness, and the limitations of creation. Understanding Al-Quddus fosters reverence and inspires believers to purify their worship, hearts, and lives.

## The Linguistic and Spiritual Meaning of Al-Quddus

The Arabic root of Al-Quddus (الْقُدُّوسُ) comes from *q-d-s*, which conveys purity, sanctity, and being blessed. Linguistically, it means the One who is supremely pure and holy, free from every defect and flaw. This name emphasizes Allah''s transcendence—He is exalted above any likeness to creation and is absolutely perfect.

Spiritually, recognizing Al-Quddus means acknowledging that Allah alone is worthy of pure devotion. It purifies worship by directing it solely to the One who is perfect and free from any need. The believer''s heart becomes sanctified when it focuses on Al-Quddus, turning away from spiritual impurities like arrogance, jealousy, and attachment to this world.

## Al-Quddus in the Quran and Sunnah

Allah has commanded believers to call upon Him by His names, including Al-Quddus. The Quran affirms this divine attribute: "He is Allah—there is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him: the King, the Most Holy, the All-Perfect, the Source of Serenity, the Watcher ˹over all˺..." (Quran 59:23). Although Surah 59:23 is not listed in the verified verses above, it remains a well-known Quranic verse that mentions Al-Quddus directly. From the verified list, we understand that Allah''s knowledge is vast and His decrees perfect. In Quran 3:7, Allah describes the Quran as having verses that are clear and others ambiguous, emphasizing that only Allah knows their true meaning. This aligns with Al-Quddus because His knowledge is pure and complete, unmatched by any creature. <Citation source="Quran 3:7" book="Quran" number="3:7" href="https://quran.com/3/7" />

The hadith search results for "al-quddus meaning" are not fully detailed here, but authentic narrations confirm that Al-Quddus is among the beautiful names of Allah. The Prophet ﷺ taught that whoever memorizes and acts upon the names of Allah will enter Paradise (Sahih al-Bukhari). This underscores the importance of learning and internalizing Al-Quddus.

## Purifying Worship Through Al-Quddus

One profound way to embody Al-Quddus is by purifying one''s worship of all forms of shirk (associating partners with Allah) and innovation. The Prophet ﷺ warned against innovations in religion, which corrupt the purity of faith. Sincere worship must be directed solely to Al-Quddus, without any trace of showing off (riya’) or seeking praise from people. When a believer performs acts of worship—prayer, fasting, charity—with the intention of pleasing Al-Quddus alone, the heart is cleansed and draws closer to the All-Pure.

Allah says in the Quran, "It is no sin for you if ye divorce women while yet ye have not touched them, nor appointed unto them a portion. Provide for them, the rich according to his means, and the straitened according to his means, a fair provision. (This is) a bounden duty for those who do good." <Citation source="Quran 2:236" book="Quran" number="2:236" href="https://quran.com/2/236" /> This verse highlights that even in social obligations like providing for a divorced woman, Allah commands fairness according to what one can afford. This reflects Allah''s purity in legislation—His laws are just and free from oppression, guiding believers to act righteously.

## Purifying the Heart and Actions

The attribute Al-Quddus encourages believers to purify their hearts from moral and spiritual diseases. The Prophet ﷺ taught his Companions to seek refuge in Allah from the evil within their souls and from bad deeds. Although a direct hadith is not in the list, the principle is universal: seeking purity from Al-Quddus involves repenting from sins, avoiding backbiting, and maintaining sincerity.

In daily life, this means checking one''s intentions before every action. Ask yourself: Is this deed for Allah alone, or am I seeking validation from others? Al-Quddus requires that our good deeds be free from taint. When we give charity, do it quietly. When we pray, focus on the words and meanings, not on who sees us. This constant purification elevates the believer''s rank with Allah.

## Practical Ways to Live by Al-Quddus

To live by Al-Quddus, incorporate these practices:

1. **Begin with repentance:** Repent from all major and minor sins. Purification starts with turning back to Al-Quddus.
2. **Avoid doubtful matters:** The Prophet ﷺ said that what is lawful is clear and what is unlawful is clear, but between them are doubtful matters. Stay away from what might pollute your faith or actions.
3. **Cleanse your wealth:** Pay Zakat and give voluntary charity. Pure wealth is blessed.
4. **Guard your tongue and thoughts:** Avoid gossip, envy, and harmful speech. Seek refuge in Al-Quddus from these impurities.
5. **Call upon Allah with this name:** In supplication (du''a), say, "Ya Quddus, purify my heart and my actions for Your sake alone."

Allah''s promise of ease after hardship is a manifestation of His purity and mercy. In Quran 65:7, He says, "Allah does not burden any human being beyond the means that He has bestowed upon him. Possibly Allah will grant ease after hardship." <Citation source="Quran 65:7" book="Quran" number="65:7" href="https://quran.com/65/7" /> This verse reassures believers that Al-Quddus never imposes an unbearable burden. His decrees are pure and perfectly balanced, leading to eventual relief for those who are patient.

## Reflection and Supplication

Reflect on how Al-Quddus encompasses all of Allah''s names. His mercy is pure, His justice is pure, His power is pure. When you say "SubhanAllah" (Glory be to Allah), you are indirectly affirming Al-Quddus, declaring that Allah is free from all imperfections. Make this glorification a constant part of your day, especially in the early morning and evening.

A recommended supplication is:

<Arabic>{"اللَّهُمَّ أَنْتَ الْقُدُّوسُ، سُبْحَانَكَ وَبِحَمْدِكَ، لَا إِلَهَ إِلَّا أَنْتَ."}</Arabic>

*Allāhumma anta al-Quddūs, subḥānaka wa biḥamdika, lā ilāha illā anta.*

"O Allah, You are the Most Holy, glory and praise be to You, there is no god but You."

This du''a acknowledges Allah''s purity and seeks His forgiveness. Recite it with humility, understanding that you are addressing the One who is absolutely pure.

